column169: XPO-Logistics contacted ERTS regarding two punctured leaking 55-Gallon DM’s containing hazardous product, EMBR12085A. A contractor dispatched and observed an estimated 30-Gallon release onto the concrete dock floor in a 10’ x 10’ area as a result of dunnage. The contractor applied oil dry to the release and overpacked both drums into 95-Gallon DF’s. The impacted absorbents, PPE, and pallet pieces were containerized into one 55-gallon DF. All waste was left on-site for XPO to manage. No storm-drains, waterways, or soil were involved in this response.

column169: On January 3, 2024, five (5) 5-gallon pails of paint were damaged in transit and released approximately one (1) gallon of product to the trailer interior. R+L Carriers retained Cura Emergency Services, LC who dispatched a crew from Green Site Services Group, Inc. (GSSG) to remediate the impacted site. The crew utilized absorbents and hand tools to remediate the site. The impacted pallet was dismantled. All impacted materials were containerized in two (2) 55-gallon drums for disposal.

column43: PRINTING INK, FLAMMABLE OR PRINTING INK RELATED MATERIAL (INCLUDING PRINTING INK THINNING OR REDUCING COMPOUND), FLAMMABLE
column169: On January 3, 2024, one (1) 55-gallon drum of printing ink was forked and released approximately 55-gallons to the dodck floor. R+L Carriers retained Cura Emergency Services, LC who dispatched crews from First Call Environmental (FCE) and Thin Line Environmental (TLE) to remediate the impacted site. R+L deployed absorbents prior to their arrival. FCE utilized hand tools to collect the absorbents. All UN1210 impacted material was collected and containerized in one (1) 85-gallon drum, one (1) 55-gallon drum, and four (4) 95-gallon overpacks. TLE personnel aided in transferring all non-damaged product to new, undamaged pallets for continued shipment.

column169: Dayton Freight personnel observed approximately ten (10) gallons of material released from one (1) 55-gallon metal drum due to the drum being punctured while loading other freight. The released material impacted the trailer floor. Dayton Freight personnel deployed granular absorbents to the impacted area and gathered the spent material and containerized it into one (1) 85-gallon poly drum. An additional one (1) 85-gallon poly drum contains the punctured 55-gallon metal drum. The generated waste was staged onsite at the terminal in a secure location. The generated waste will remain onsite for Dayton Freight’s contracted hazardous waste vendor to coordinate disposal.

column169: On January 3, 2024, sixteen (16) pails of paint (gallon and quart) were crushed and released approximately eight (8) gallons of product to the trailer interior. R+L Carriers retained Cura Emergency Services, LC who dispatched a crew from Lone Star Hazmat (LSH) to remediate the impacted site. LSH utilized absorbents and hand tools to remediate the site. All waste was containerized in three (3) 55-gallon drums and nine (9) 5-gallon pails.
